DigitalReadOut.qml: set default values for machine with 5+ axes

title: DigitalReadOut.qml: set default values for machine with 5+ axes
message:
DigitalReadOut.qml: set default values for machine with 5+ axes

In DigitalReadOut.qml, it assume the default axes number is 4.
Therefore, the dtg, g5xOffset,g92Offset, toolOffset, and basePosition
are array with 4 elements.
Increase those to 9 elements for machines with 5 or more axes.

message.proto: do not export mkwrapper messages to nanopb/RT

title: message.proto: do not export mkwrapper messages to nanopb/RT
message:
message.proto: do not export mkwrapper messages to nanopb/RT

the [(nanopb).type = FT_IGNORE] option tells the nanopb generator to
ignore this field, meaning no descriptor references are added to the
generated C code.

This is good practice for messages which are never used in RT. Otherwise,
the corresponding .c file needs to linked into the pbmsgs module
(see src/machinetalk/msgcomponents/Submakefile) and the corresponding
extern reference exported in pbmsgs.c .

This also removes "missing symbol" messages during a kthreads build.

title: nanopb.proto: add back in again
message:
nanopb.proto: add back in again

This broke external (i.e. non-machinekit builds) like QtQuickVCP

we'll keep nanopb.proto in machinetalk-protobuf and check during
the machinekit build if the nanopb.proto file from this repo differs
from the one which is brought into the machinekit repo as a git subtree
from machinekit/nanopb (pathname src/machinetalk/nanopb/generator/proto/nanopb.proto)

Since the change frequency of nanopb.proto is fairly low and external builds
are unlikely to use the nanopb options, using an outdated nanopb.proto
in an external build is unlikely to cause issues

title: Container: prune fields for RT usage
message:
Container: prune fields for RT usage

the nanopb bindings will not generate, or understand fields which are
tagged with [(nanopb).type = FT_IGNORE]. This helps bring down the size
of the pb_Message struct.

The goal is to have serialisation/deserialisation happen at the RT boundary
in userland and only ship the nanopb-generated pbMessage struct over the
ringbuffer, which is about 6.5K without those options.

built only with cmake.

title: ZMQContext: Calling method 'createSocket' without specifying a parent pointer…
message:
ZMQContext: Calling method 'createSocket' without specifying a parent pointer now doesn't implicitly set 'ZMQContext' instance as parent anymore.

CAUTION: This breaks compatibility with older code which assumes the socket instance is implicitly managed by its associated context instance if no parent is specified. So this causes memory leaks in such cases.

title: ZMQSocket,ZMQContext: Handle closing/deleting 'ZMQSocket' and 'ZMQContext' instances correctly.
message:
ZMQSocket,ZMQContext: Handle closing/deleting 'ZMQSocket' and 'ZMQContext' instances correctly.

Method 'ZMQSocket::close()' now is a slot and also unregisters instance from its 'ZMQContext' instance.
Deleting a 'ZMQContext' now doesn't delete 'ZMQSocket' instances anymore. Instead, the socket is closed and its pointer to the associated context is set to 0.

merge: Change PollingZMQContext::poll to empty the socket queue rather than poll once per interval

title: Wrap the call to poll with try/catch
message:
Wrap the call to poll with try/catch

Without this, an error in poll() will cause mayhem as an exception is thrown
in a Qt event handler, causing an abort with a nasty message.

title: Modify the PollingZMQContext::poll to repeatedly poll until no data
message:
Modify the PollingZMQContext::poll to repeatedly poll until no data

With the way the poll was set up, if your interval was 10ms (default), you
would only get a maximum of 100 messages per socket as poll will only take the
first message from each available socket.  This was not nearly enough for my
use where the peak is into the thousands per second on a socket, so I have
modified the code to repeatedly poll while there is still data to poll.

This should empty the socket queue before returning to singleShot delay again.

Until now, I dont't have a 'QSocketNotifier' based solution that works with REQ-REP protocol in all conditions. So I decided to drop support until a gerneral solution is available. Correspondingly, I closed gh-2 and created a new feature request gh-4.

Note that 'PollingZMQSocket' supports all kinds of protocols, so if REQ-REP is needed that class can be used instead, which is the default implementation anyway.

title: refactoring: Allow different message event loop implementations.
message:
refactoring: Allow different message event loop implementations.

This change provides two different implementations:
1. A new polling-based implementation.
2. The old (and still buggy) QSocketNotifier implementation.

The new polling-based implementation consists of the two classes 'PollingZMQContext' and 'PollingZMQSocket'. The old one is now implemented by the two classes 'SocketNotifierZMQSocket' and 'SocketNotifierZMQContext'.

All examples now use the polling-based mechanism, because this one works with all ZMQ interaction protocols without any known issues. Furthermore, it allows fine grained timing control.

title: bugfix,gh-1: Merged bugfix of Jelle Hissink, which fixes gh-1.
message:
bugfix,gh-1: Merged bugfix of Jelle Hissink, which fixes gh-1.

Here is the corresponding issue description given by Jelle:

"
When I create a SUB socket on tcp (either localhost or ip) I get continuous notifications on the socketActivity() slot, this prevents QTimer from running correctly.
The source of the continuous calls is in the socketNotifyWrite_ notifier. Inside this call to socketActivity flags() always returns 0 and socketActivity() will be called again immediately flooding the event loop.
I made a small modification to the source to prevent this by disabeling the notifier when flags() returns 0 and enabeling it again if sending fails because sending would block.
"

NOTE: During the merge I ignored line break changes in order to get a clean change set.
.
